The chlorine equipment is maintained by the facility employees with annual inspections by the chlorine vendor and that company also maintains the alarm system.  All necessary parts that might be required to repair the anticipated types of leaks are available on site.  Facility employees audit the facility to maintain emergency equipment, communication equipment and their training status.

The Planada Community Services District has worked with the local emergency responders such as the Fire Department, the Police Department, the local HAZMAT group and the local Certified Unified Program Agency (CUPA) to ensure that all parties are aware of the emergency response plan and know what to do in the event of an accidental release of chlorine.

Purpose:

1 Protect Planada Community Services District employees, nearby residences and the public from the potential harm of uncontrolled release of chlorine both on and off the site;

2. Provide information for onsite emergency responders to use to access the hazard of a release or threatened release of chlorine;

3. Establish procedures for activation of this plan and the emergency response to an uncontrolled releases; 

4. Comply with the requirements of Section (r) of the Clean Air Act;

5. Provide Emergency Response agencies with relevant information for responding to an incident at this facility; 

6. Facilitate the coordination of emergency communications to potentially affected residents of the community.


Stan Rodriguez                                                                              
Facility Manager                                                                     Date: 10/07/09
